I drove by the Peace Arch a couple of years ago.  (I was going to Vancouver for
a Country Dance &amp; Song Society Executive Committee meeeting, not that it
matters.)  Looked at the arch, slowly, from the car, since there was a backup
at the border crossing.  Got out of the car - I was a passenger, not driving -
went and looked at the inscription, rejoined the car, which had moved about 10
feet.

I took a moment wondering what the deal was with a Peace Arch in 1914, and how
ironic that was what with WWI on the horizon, and then I realized that it
commemorated the 100th anniversary of the end of the war of 1812.

And to put that another way, the frickin' war of 1812 was only 7 years further
downtime of the building of the arch than the building of the arch is downtime
from us today.  We pack a bunch of history into a short time on this side of
the Atlantic.

[The next year I got a little jolt at Jamestown, VA, looking at a plaque from
the &quot;Jamestown Jubilee&quot;, the big 200th anniversary celebration of the landing
that they held in 1807.  They had a big 300th anniversary celebration and
Exposition last century, and they, uh, rebuilt the visitor's center for this
year.]

-- Alan
